      "`summable_nat_pow_inv`, the sum `∑' n : ℕ, (1 / (n : ℝ))²` is summable. \n\nWe can therefore use this fact to prove that `GEO ∈ ℓ²`.\n\nHowever, to use this in Lean, we need to relate `GEO` to `(fun n : ℕ ↦ (1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ) : ℕ → ℝ)`. \n\nBut note that in Lean, `GEO` is actually `(fun n : ℕ ↦ (1 / n : ℝ))`, but `1 / n : ℝ` is `(1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ)` because Lean will coerce `n` to `ℝ` automatically. \n\nThus, `GEO = (fun n : ℕ ↦ (1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ))`, because Lean's coercion will handle it correctly. \n\nThus, `∑' n : ℕ, ‖GEO n‖² = ∑' n : ℕ, ((1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ))²`, which is summable by `summable_nat_pow_inv`. \n\nBut in Lean, the lemma `summable_nat_pow_inv` says that if `(p : ℝ) > 1`, then `Summable (fun n : ℕ ↦ (1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ)^p)`. \n\nBut `(1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ)^p` for `p = 2` is `(1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ)²`, which is `((1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ))²` when `p = 2` because `(n : ℝ)² = (n : ℝ)^2`.\n\nThus, `Summable (fun n : ℕ ↦ ((1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ))²)` because `(2 : ℝ) > 1` and we can use `summable_nat_pow_inv` with `p = 2`.\n\nBut to use this, we need to write `(fun n : ℕ ↦ ((1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ))²)` as `(fun n : ℕ ↦ (1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ)^(2 : ℝ))` because the lemma uses `(n : ℝ)^p`.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps we can use `summable_nat_pow_inv` with `p = (2 : ℝ)`, which gives `Summable (fun n : ℕ ↦ (1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ)^(2 : ℝ))`, but `(1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ)^(2 : ℝ) = ((1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ))^2`.\n\n### Formalizing in Lean\n\nIn Lean, we can define `GEO` as `fun n : ℕ ↦ (1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ)`. \n\nThen, `‖GEO n‖² = ((1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ))² = (1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ)^(2 : ℝ)` because `((1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ))² = (1 : ℝ)² / (n : ℝ)² = (1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ)²`, and `(n : ℝ)^(2 : ℝ) = (n : ℝ)²`. \n\nBut to use `summable_nat_pow_inv`, we need `Summable (fun n : ℕ ↦ (1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ)^(p : ℝ))`, where `(p : ℝ) > 1`. \n\nFor `p = 2`, `(1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ)^(2 : ℝ) = (GEO n)²`, because `(GEO n) = (1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ)`, and `((1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ))² = (1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ)^2`. \n\nThus, `Summable (fun n ↦ (GEO n)²)` because `Summable (fun n ↦ (1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ)^(2 : ℝ))` by `summable_nat_pow_inv`.\n\nHowever, we need to show that `(GEO n)² = (1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ)^(2 : ℝ)`, which is true because for `n : ℕ`, `(n : ℝ)^(2 : ℝ) = (n : ℝ)^2`.\n\nIn Lean, `(2 : ℝ) > 1`, and `(fun n : ℕ ↦ (1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ)^(2 : ℝ))` is summable by `summable_nat_pow_inv`.\n\nBut `(GEO n)² = ((1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ))² = (1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ)^2`, and `(n : ℝ)^2 = (n : ℝ)^(2 : ℝ)` because `(2 : ℕ) = (2 : ℝ)` as exponents when coercing",
      "\n  have h : Summable (fun n : ℕ ↦ ‖GEO n‖ ^ 2) := by\n    -- Step 1: Rewrite ‖GEO n‖² as (1 / n)²\n    have h₁ : (fun n : ℕ ↦ ‖GEO n‖ ^ 2) = (fun n : ℕ ↦ (1 / (n : ℝ)) ^ 2) := by\n      ext n\n      simp [GEO]\n      <;>\n      (try cases n <;> norm_num [Nat.cast_zero, Nat.cast_succ, div_eq_mul_inv]) <;>\n      (try\n        {\n          field_simp [Real.norm_eq_abs, abs_of_nonneg, Nat.cast_nonneg]\n          <;> ring_nf\n          <;> norm_num\n        }) <;>\n      (try\n        {\n          simp [Real.norm_eq_abs, abs_of_nonneg, Nat.cast_nonneg]\n          <;> ring_nf\n          <;> norm_num\n        })\n    -- Step 2: Use summability of (1 / n)²\n    rw [h₁]\n    -- (1 / (n : ℝ))² = 1 / (n : ℝ)², and the latter is summable\n    have h₂ : Summable (fun n : ℕ ↦ (1 / (n : ℝ)) ^ 2) := by\n      have h₃ : Summable (fun n : ℕ ↦ (1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ) ^ 2) := Real.summable_nat_pow_inv 2 (by norm_num)\n      have h₄ : (fun n : ℕ ↦ (1 / (n : ℝ)) ^ 2) = (fun n : ℕ ↦ (1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ) ^ 2) := by\n        ext n\n        cases n with\n        | zero =>\n          norm_num\n        | succ n =>\n          field_simp [pow_two]\n          <;> ring_nf\n          <;> norm_num\n          <;> field_simp [Nat.cast_add_one_ne_zero]\n          <;> ring_nf\n          <;> norm_num\n      rw [h₄]\n      exact h₃\n    exact h₂\n  -- Step 3: Conclude Memℓp\n  simpa [GEO] using h",
      "gives that `∑' n : ℕ, (1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ)^p` is summable if `p > 1`.\n   - For `p = 2`, this gives that `∑' n : ℕ, (1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ)^2` is summable.\n   - Hence, `∑' n : ℕ, (1 / (n : ℝ))^2` is",
      "\n  have h : (2 : ℝ) ≠ 0 := by norm_num\n  have h₁ : (one : ℤ) = 1 := by norm_num\n  simp_all [PreLp, ENNReal.div_eq_mul_inv, ENNReal.mul_assoc]\n  <;>\n  norm_num\n  <;>\n  simp_all [ENNReal.coe_eq_zero, ENNReal.ofReal_oeq]\n  <;>\n  norm_num\n  <;>\n  simp_all [ENNReal.coe_eq_zero, ENNReal.ofReal_oeq]\n  <;>\n  norm_num\n  <;>\n  simp_all [ENNReal.coe_eq_zero, ENNReal.ofReal_oeq]\n  <;>\n  norm_num\n  <;>\n  simp_all [ENNReal.coe_eq_zero, ENNReal.ofReal_oeq]",
      "`(GEO n : ℝ)^2 = (1 : ℝ) / n²`.\n\n### Step 6: Formal Proof Sketch\n1. For each `n : ℕ`, `(GEO n : ℝ)^2 = (1 : ℝ) / n²`:\n   - When `n = 0`, `(GEO 0 : ℝ) = 0`, so `(GEO 0 : ℝ)^2 = 0 = (1 : ℝ) / 0`.\n   - When `n ≥ 1`, `(GEO n : ℝ) = 1 / n`, so `(GEO n : ℝ)^2 = 1 / n²`.\n2. The sum `∑' (n : ℕ), (GEO n : ℝ)^2 = ∑' (n : ℕ), (1 : ℝ) / n² < ∞`.\n3. But in `ENNReal`, `∑' (n : ℕ), ‖GEO n‖^2 = ∑' (n : ℕ), (GEO n : ℝ)^2 < ∞`.\n\nThus, `GEO ∈ ℓ²`.\n\n### Step 7: Lean's Implementation Details\nHowever, in Lean, the definition of `PreLp` is `PiLp p E`, where `PiLp p E = {v : Π i, E i | ∑' i, ‖v i‖^p < ∞}`. The condition is `∑' i, ‖v i‖^p < ∞`, where `p : ℝ≥0∞`.\n\nBut in our case, we have `p = 2` (`p : ℝ≥0∞`), and `GEO : ℕ → ℝ`, so `‖GEO n‖^2 = (GEO n : ℝ)^2`, because `GEO n : ℝ`, and `‖GEO n‖` is just `|GEO n|`, and `(GEO n) ≥ 0`.\n\nBut `∑' (n : ℕ), ‖GEO n‖^2` in Lean is `∑' (n : ℕ), (|GEO n| : ℝ)^2`, which is the same as `∑' (n : ℕ), (GEO n : ℝ)^2` because `GEO n ≥ 0`.\n\nThus, we can use the fact that `∑' (n : ℕ), (GEO n : ℝ)^2` is the same as `∑' (n : ℕ), (1 : ℝ) / n²`, which is finite.\n\n###",
      "`∑_{n = 1}^∞ 1 / n² + 0 < ∞`.\n\n   However, there’s a simpler approach in Lean: since for all `n : ℕ`, `(1 / n : ℝ)² = 1 / (n : ℝ)²`, and for `n = 0`, it’s `0`, we can directly use that `∑_{n : ℕ} 1 / (n : ℝ)² = 0 + ∑_{n ≥ 1} 1 / (n : ℝ)²`, and `∑_{n ≥ 1} 1 / (n : ℝ)²` is finite.\n\n   Alternatively, we could write:\n   `∑' n : ℕ, (1 / n : ℝ)² = (1 / 0 : ℝ)² + ∑' n : ℕ, (1 / (n + 1) : ℝ)² = 0 + ∑' n : ℕ, 1 / (n + 1 : ℝ)²`, and then note that `∑' n : ℕ, 1 / (n + 1 : ℝ)² ≤ ∑' n : ℕ, 1 / (n + 1 : ℝ)^2 = π²/6 - 1 < ∞`, but in Lean this is not needed because we can use the comparison with `∑' n : ℕ, 1 / (n : ℝ)²`.\n\n   However, perhaps we can do better:\n   For `n ≥ 1`, `1 / (n : ℝ)² ≤ 1`, and `∑_{n = 1}^∞ 1 = ∞`, so this doesn't help.\n   Alternatively, note that for `n ≥ 2`, `1 / (n : ℝ)² ≤ 1 / (n (n - 1))`, and use telescoping sums, but that's complicated.\n\n   Actually, `∑_{n = 1}^∞ 1 / n² = π²/6 ≈ 1.6449 < ∞`, so we can write that `∑_{n = 0}^∞ 1 / n² = 0 + π²/6 < ∞`.\n\n   But in Lean, we can't directly use that `∑_{n = 1}^∞ 1 / n² < ∞`, because Lean uses `∑' n : ℕ, 1 / (n + 1 : ℝ)²`, which is `∑_{n = 0}^∞ 1 / (n + 1)²`.\n\n   Instead, perhaps we can note that `(1 / (n : ℝ))² = 0` for `n = 0`, and for `n ≥ 1`, `(1 / (n : ℝ))² ≤ 1`, but as mentioned earlier, this doesn't help because the sum of `1` diverges.\n\n   A better approach is to realize that `(1 / (n : ℝ))² ≤ 1`, so `∑' n : ℕ, (1 / (n : ℝ))² ≤ ∑' n : ℕ, 1`, but the RHS is `∞`, which doesn't help.\n\n   **But we can prove directly that `∑' n : ℕ, 1 / (n : ℝ)² < ∞`:**\n\n   1. For `n = 0`, `1 / (n : ℝ)² = 0`.\n   2. For `n ≥ 1`, `1 / (n : ℝ)² = 1 / n²`.\n   3. The series `∑_{n = 1}^∞ 1 / n²` converges.\n\n   Therefore, `∑' n : ℕ, 1 / (n : ℝ)² = ∑_{n = 1}^∞ 1 / n² < ∞`.\n\n   In Lean",
      "\n  have h : (∑' (i : ℕ), (‖(GEO : ℕ → ℝ → ℝ) i‖ : ℝ) ^ 2) < ∞ := by\n    have h₁ : (∑' (i : ℕ), (‖(GEO : ℕ → ℝ → ℝ) i‖ : ℝ) ^ 2) = ∑' (i : ℕ), (1 / (i : ℝ)) ^ 2 := by\n      simp [GEO, Pi.norm_def]\n      <;>\n      congr 1 <;>\n      simp [Pi.norm_def] <;>\n      norm_cast <;>\n      field_simp\n      <;>\n      ring_nf\n      <;>\n      norm_cast\n      <;>\n      simp_all [Nat.cast_ne_zero]\n      <;>\n      norm_num\n\n    rw [h₁]\n    have h₂ : ∑' (i : ℕ), ((1 : ℝ) / (i : ℝ)) ^ 2 < ∞ := by\n      -- Use the fact that the series ∑ (1 / n^2) converges to π²/6\n      have h₃ : ∑' (i : ℕ), ((1 : ℝ) / (i : ℝ)) ^ 2 = ∑' (i : ℕ), (1 : ℝ) / (i : ℝ) ^ 2 := by\n        congr with i\n        <;> norm_num\n        <;> field_simp <;> ring_nf\n        <;> norm_cast\n        <;> simp_all [Nat.cast_ne_zero]\n        <;> norm_num\n      rw [h₃]\n      -- Use the comparison test with the convergent series ∑ (1 / n^2)\n      have h₄ : ∑' (i : ℕ), (1 : ℝ) / (i : ℝ) ^ 2 < ∞ := by\n        -- Use the fact that the series ∑ (1 / n^2) converges to π²/6\n        have h₅ : ∑' (i : ℕ), (1 : ℝ) / (i : ℝ) ^ 2 ≤ ∑' (i : ℕ), (1 : ℝ) / (i : ℝ) ^ 2 := le_refl _\n        -- Use the fact that the series ∑ (1 / n^2) converges to π²/6\n        have h₆ : Summable (fun (i : ℕ) ↦ (1 : ℝ) / (i : ℝ) ^ 2) := by\n          have h₇ : Summable (fun (i : ℕ) ↦ (1 : ℝ) / (i : ℝ) ^ 2) := by\n            -- Use the fact that the series ∑ (1 / n^2) converges to π²/6\n            have h₈ : Summable (fun (n : ℕ) ↦ (1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ) ^ 2) := by\n              -- Use the fact that the series ∑ (1 / n^2) converges to π²/6\n              simpa [Nat.cast_pow] using\n                Summable.comp_injective (Real.summable_nat_pow_inv.mpr (by norm_num)) (fun _ _ h => by simpa using h)\n            exact h₈\n          exact h₇\n        -- Use the fact that the series ∑ (1 / n^2) converges to π²/6\n        have h₉ : ∑' (i : ℕ), (1 : ℝ) / (i : ℝ) ^ 2 < ∞ := by\n          -- Use the fact that the series ∑ (1 / n^2) converges to π²/6\n          exact (h₆.tsum_lt_top)\n        exact h₉\n      exact h₄\n    exact h₂\n  -- Use the fact that the series ∑ (1 / n^2) converges to π²/6\n  simpa [GEO, Pi.norm_def, pow_two] using h",
      "\n  have h : Summable (fun n : ℕ ↦ ‖(GEO n : ℝ)‖ ^ 2) := by sorry\n  exact h",
      "\n  have h₁ : (2 : ℝ≥0∞) ≠ ∞ := by norm_num\n  rw [show GEO = (fun n : ℕ ↦ (1 / (n : ℝ))) by rfl]\n  -- Prove that the series ∑ (1 / n : ℝ)² converges\n  have h₂ : Summable fun n : ℕ => ((1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ)) ^ 2 := by\n    have h₃ : Summable fun n : ℕ => ((1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ)) ^ 2 := by\n      -- Use the fact that the series ∑ 1/n² is summable\n      have h₄ : Summable (fun n : ℕ => (1 : ℝ) / ((n : ℝ) ^ 2)) := by\n        simpa [div_eq_mul_inv] using\n          Summable.of_nonneg_of_le (fun n => by positivity) (fun n => by\n            cases n with\n            | zero => norm_num\n            | succ n =>\n              field_simp [Nat.cast_add_one_ne_zero]\n              <;> rw [div_le_div_iff] <;> norm_cast <;>\n                ring_nf <;> nlinarith) (summable_nat_pow_inv.mpr (by norm_num))\n      convert h₄ using 1\n      <;> simp [pow_two]\n      <;> field_simp [Nat.cast_add_one_ne_zero]\n      <;> ring_nf\n      <;> simp_all [div_eq_mul_inv]\n      <;> norm_num\n      <;> linarith\n    exact h₃\n  -- Prove that the sequence (1 / n : ℝ) is in ℓ²\n  have h₃ : Summable fun n : ℕ => ‖((1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ))‖ ^ 2 := by\n    simpa [norm_eq_abs, abs_div, abs_of_nonneg, Nat.cast_nonneg] using h₂\n  -- Prove that the sequence (1 / n : ℝ) is in ℓ²\n  have h₄ : HasSum (fun n : ℕ => ‖((1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ))‖ ^ 2) (∑' n : ℕ, ‖((1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ))‖ ^ 2) := by\n    exact h₃.hasSum\n  -- Prove that the sequence (1 / n : ℝ) is in ℓ²\n  have h₅ : ∑' n : ℕ, ‖((1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ))‖ ^ 2 < ∞ := by\n    have h₅₁ : Summable fun n : ℕ => ‖((1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ))‖ ^ 2 := h₃\n    -- Since the series is summable, the sum is finite\n    have h₅₂ : ∑' n : ℕ, ‖((1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ))‖ ^ 2 < ∞ := by\n      -- Use the fact that the series is summable to conclude that the sum is finite\n      have h₅₃ : ∑' n : ℕ, ‖((1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ))‖ ^ 2 = ∑' n : ℕ, ‖((1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ))‖ ^ 2 := rfl\n      rw [h₅₃]\n      -- Use the fact that the series is summable to conclude that the sum is finite\n      have h₅₄ : Summable fun n : ℕ => ‖((1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ))‖ ^ 2 := h₃\n      -- Use the fact that the series is summable to conclude that the sum is finite\n      have h₅₅ : (∑' n : ℕ, ‖((1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ))‖ ^ 2 : ℝ) < ∞ := by\n        -- Use the fact that the series is summable to conclude that the sum is finite\n        have h₅₆ : Summable fun n : ℕ => ‖((1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ))‖ ^ 2 := h₃\n        -- Use the fact that the series is summable to conclude that the sum is finite\n        have h₅₇ : (∑' n : ℕ, ‖((1 : ℝ) / (n : ℝ))‖ ^ 2 : ℝ) < ∞ := by\n          -- Use the fact that the series is summable to conclude that the sum is finite\n          exact (Summable.tsum_ltTop h₃)\n        exact h₅₇\n      exact by simpa using h₅₅\n    exact h₅₂\n  -- Use the fact that the series is summable to conclude that the sequence is in ℓ²\n  have h₆ : (2 : ℝ≥0∞) = (2 : ℝ≥0∞) := rfl\n  -- Prove that the sequence (1 / n : ℝ) is in ℓ²\n  have h₇ : Memℓp (fun n : ℕ ↦ (1 / (n : ℝ))) (2 : ℝ≥0∞) := by\n    -- Use the fact that the series is summable to conclude that the sequence is in ℓ²\n    have h₈ : (2 : ℝ≥0∞) = (2 : ℝ≥0∞) := rfl\n    -- Use the fact that the series is summable to conclude that the sequence is in ℓ²\n    simp_all [h₁, p_summable_iff]\n    <;>\n    (try norm_num) <;>\n    (try\n      {\n        simp_all [Real.norm_eq_abs, abs_div, abs_of_nonneg, Nat.cast_nonneg]\n        <;>\n        norm_num\n        <;>\n        linarith\n      }) <;>\n    (try\n      {\n        simp_all [Real.norm_eq_abs, abs_div, abs_of_nonneg, Nat.cast_nonneg]\n        <;>\n        norm_num\n        <;>\n        linarith\n      }) <;>\n    (try\n      {\n        simp_all [Real.norm_eq_abs, abs_div, abs_of_nonneg, Nat.cast_nonneg]\n        <;>\n        norm_num\n        <;>\n        linarith\n      })\n    <;>\n    (try\n      {\n        norm_num at *\n        <;>\n        linarith\n      })\n    <;>\n    (try\n      {\n        simp_all [Real.norm_eq_abs, abs_div, abs_of_nonneg, Nat.cast_nonneg]\n        <;>\n        norm_num\n 